NLP Australian legal case data¶

  • Legal documents are generally written in complex legal language. Often, these documents are hard to understand, especially when it comes to contracts, piece of legislation and court records. Interpretation into Plain English and creation of summaries for lengthy documents require a lot of time and money. Law firms hire a large number of support employees to perform these types of tasks. One way to minimize the effort and cost is developing NLP in Machine learning algorithm, which creates summaries of legal texts using topic modeling techniques knows as Latent Dirichlet Allocation(LDA).

  • The dataset contains Australian legal around 4000 cases from the Federal Court of Australia (FCA) for the year 2006,2007,2008 and 2009. This data was accessed from UCI machine learning repository.

Parsing XML file to dataframe¶

  • The data consists of around 4000 separate XML files of individual legal cases.
  • First step is parsing these files to convert them into pandas data frame for further use.

# function to short files base on numerical number from the folder
numbers = re.compile(r'(\d+)')
def numericalSort(value):
    parts = numbers.split(value)
    parts[1::2] = map(int, parts[1::2])
    return parts

# convert XML files into pandas dataframe 

file_path="/Users/akshay/Downloads/ADP_challange/corpus-2/fulltext/*.xml"
files=sorted(glob.glob(file_path),key=numericalSort)
lst=[]
rows = []
df_cols = ["name", "link", "catchphrases", "sentences"]


def xml_dataframe(xml_files):
    for ind,file in enumerate(xml_files):
        # read xml files
        with open(file, "r",encoding="utf8", errors='ignore') as file:
            soup = BeautifulSoup(file, "html.parser",exclude_encodings='0xe9')
            # extract name
            name=soup.find('name')
            s_name=name.get_text(' ',strip=False)
            
            # extract website link
            link=soup.find('austlii')
            s_link=link.get_text(',',strip=True)
            
            # extract catchphrases
            catchphrases=soup.find('catchphrases')
            s_catch=catchphrases.get_text(',',strip=True)
            
            # extract sentences
            sentences=soup.find('sentences')
            s_sent=sentences.get_text(',',strip=True)
    
    # create dictionary for name, aystlii, catchphrases and sentence and append in the list
        rows.append({"name": s_name, "link": s_link,"catchphrases": s_catch, "sentences": s_sent})
        #rows.append({"name": s_name, "link": s_link,"catchphrases": s_catch})


    out_df = pd.DataFrame(rows, columns = df_cols)
    
    return out_df

Data cleaning and text preprocessing¶

Tokenization, Lemmatization and Stopwords handling¶

Text data is converted into a machine readable format to develop machine learning solution:¶
  • removing sentences related to case owners info, filing, decisions dates, etc
  • keeping words that start with letters and removing non-letter words and characters
  • removing extra spaces
  • converting all characters to lower case and splitting words
  • lemmatization to remove suffix of words but keeping meaning of the original word
In [6]:
# function for text preprocessing
wl = WordNetLemmatizer()  # bettwer way to remove suffix by keping meaning of the full words

def text_processing(row):
    review = row.partition('Associate:')[0] # remove endings of sentences after 'Associate:' which contain only information regarding dates and companies/person involved in the case 
    review = re.sub('[^a-zA-Z]', ' ', row) # match all strings that start with a letter, the second means match all strings that contain a non-letter
    review = re.sub(r'(?:^| )\w(?:$| )', ' ', review) # remove other characters and numbers from the string
    review = re.sub(' +', ' ', review) # remove extra spaces from string 
    review = review.lower() # lower case
    review = review.split() # split words
    #wl = WordNetLemmatizer()  # bettwer way to remove suffix but keping meaning of the full words
    review = [wl.lemmatize(word) for word in review if not word in set(stopwords.words('english'))] # remove most common english stop words such as a,an, the in ,on etc
    review = ' '.join(review)
    return review

Topic modelling for Legal documents¶

  • Topic modeling is statistical modeling for finding topics that occur in the collection of documents.
  • LDAs approach to topic modeling is considering each document as a collection of topics in a certain proportion, while each topic as a collection of keywords, again, in a certain proportion.
  • LDA builds topic per document model and words per topic model, modelled as Dirichlet distributions.

  • LDA rearranges topic distribution within the document and keyword distribution within each topic to obtain a good composition of topic-keywords Dirichlet distribution.

  • Topics Modelling would identify different topics in legal documents, which could be next summarized.

  • gensim library for NLP is used to impliment LDA.

  • text from 'sentences' column is transformed into LDA compatible format

LDA with gensim¶

n-gram and dictionary of words with index¶

  • split the text and generate the n-gram ( unigram, bigram, tri-gram and so on )
  • create a dictionary from the data using gensim corpora ( every term assigned as index )
  • we keep first 100000 most frequent tokens
  • filter out terms, which occur in less than 15 articles and more then 70% of the articles
In [12]:
# function to generate n-gram
n=1
def n_gram(row):
    ngrm = nltk.ngrams(row,n) # bigram # monogram
    blst = list(ngrm)
    text = ' '.join(['_'.join(i)for i in blst])
    text=text.split()
    return text
In [13]:
# transform dataframe into required format
df1['sentence_process_list'] = df1['sentence_process'].apply(lambda x: x.split())
df1['sentence_process_ngram'] = df1.sentence_process_list.apply(n_gram)

# Creating the term dictionary of our corpus, where each unique term is assigned an index. 
dictionary = corpora.Dictionary(df1.sentence_process_ngram)
#keep only the first 100000 most frequent tokens. Filter out terms which occur in less than 15 articles & more than 70% of the articles 
dictionary.filter_extremes(no_below=15, no_above=0.7, keep_n=100000) # tune for better result

LDA performance criteria¶

  • Unsupervised LDA model is checked based on its perplexity and coherence score. Lower perplexity and higher coherence scores are better.

Dominant topics and percentage contribution to each topics¶

  • using LDA with tfidf embedding
  • dominant topics are identified based on their percentage contribution and relevancy of keywords for each documents
In [20]:
data = df1.sentences.values.tolist()

def format_topics_sentences(ldamodel=None, corpus=tfidf_corpus, texts=data):
    # Init output
    sent_topics_df = pd.DataFrame()

    # Get main topic in each document
    for i, row_list in enumerate(ldamodel[corpus]):
        row = row_list[0] if ldamodel.per_word_topics else row_list            
        # print(row)
        row = sorted(row, key=lambda x: (x[1]), reverse=True)
        # Get the Dominant topic, Percentage Contribution and Keywords for each document
        for j, (topic_num, prop_topic) in enumerate(row):
            if j == 0:  # => dominant topic
                wp = ldamodel.show_topic(topic_num)
                topic_keywords = ", ".join([word for word, prop in wp])
                sent_topics_df = sent_topics_df.append(pd.Series([int(topic_num), round(prop_topic,4), topic_keywords]), ignore_index=True)
            else:
                break
    sent_topics_df.columns = ['Dominant_Topic', 'Perc_Contribution', 'Topic_Keywords']

    # Add original text to the end of the output
    contents = pd.Series(texts)
    sent_topics_df = pd.concat([sent_topics_df, contents], axis=1)
    return(sent_topics_df)

def topics_per_document(model, corpus, start=0, end=1):
    corpus_sel = corpus[start:end]
    dominant_topics = []
    topic_percentages = []
    for i, corp in enumerate(corpus_sel):
        topic_percs, wordid_topics, wordid_phivalues = model[corp]
        dominant_topic = sorted(topic_percs, key = lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[0][0]
        dominant_topics.append((i, dominant_topic))
        topic_percentages.append(topic_percs)
    return(dominant_topics, topic_percentages)


dominant_topics, topic_percentages = topics_per_document(model=lda_model, corpus=bow_corpus, end=-1)            


# Distribution of Dominant Topics in Each Document
df = pd.DataFrame(dominant_topics, columns=['Document_Id', 'Dominant_Topic'])
dominant_topic_in_each_doc = df.groupby('Dominant_Topic').size()
df_dominant_topic_in_each_doc = dominant_topic_in_each_doc.to_frame(name='count').reset_index()

# Total Topic Distribution by actual weight
topic_weightage_by_doc = pd.DataFrame([dict(t) for t in topic_percentages])
df_topic_weightage_by_doc = topic_weightage_by_doc.sum().to_frame(name='count').reset_index()

# Top 3 Keywords for each Topic
topic_top3words = [(i, topic) for i, topics in lda_model.show_topics(formatted=False) 
                                 for j, (topic, wt) in enumerate(topics) if j < 3]

# Get topic weights and dominant topics ------------
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_file, show
from bokeh.models import Label
from bokeh.io import output_notebook

# Get topic weights
topic_weights = []
for i, row_list in enumerate(lda_model[bow_corpus]):
    topic_weights.append([w for i, w in row_list[0]])

# Array of topic weights    
arr = pd.DataFrame(topic_weights).fillna(0).values

# Keep the well separated points (optional)
arr = arr[np.amax(arr, axis=1) > 0.35]

# Dominant topic number in each doc
topic_num = np.argmax(arr, axis=1)

# tSNE Dimension Reduction
tsne_model = TSNE(n_components=2, verbose=1, random_state=0, angle=.99, init='pca')
tsne_lda = tsne_model.fit_transform(arr)

# Plot the Topic Clusters using Bokeh
output_notebook()
n_topics = 10
mycolors = np.array([color for name, color in mcolors.TABLEAU_COLORS.items()])
plot = figure(title="t-SNE Clustering of {} LDA Topics".format(n_topics), 
              plot_width=700, plot_height=400)
plot.scatter(x=tsne_lda[:,0], y=tsne_lda[:,1], color=mycolors[topic_num])
show(plot)
